#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:6
msgid "How to use temporary directories and files in tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:9
msgid "The ``tmp_path`` fixture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:11
msgid ""
"You can use the ``tmp_path`` fixture which will provide a temporary "
"directory unique to the test invocation, created in the `base temporary "
"directory`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:15
msgid ""
"``tmp_path`` is a :class:`pathlib.Path` object. Here is an example test "
"usage:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:17
msgid ""
"# content of test_tmp_path.py\n"
"CONTENT = \"content\"\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_create_file(tmp_path):\n"
"    d = tmp_path / \"sub\"\n"
"    d.mkdir()\n"
"    p = d / \"hello.txt\"\n"
"    p.write_text(CONTENT, encoding=\"utf-8\")\n"
"    assert p.read_text(encoding=\"utf-8\") == CONTENT\n"
"    assert len(list(tmp_path.iterdir())) == 1\n"
"    assert 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:32
msgid ""
"Running this would result in a passed test except for the last ``assert 0`` "
"line which we use to look at values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:35
msgid ""
"$ pytest test_tmp_path.py\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-7.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"rootdir: /home/sweet/project\n"
"collected 1 item\n"
"\n"
"test_tmp_path.py F                                                   [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"_____________________________ test_create_file "
"_____________________________\n"
"\n"
"tmp_path = PosixPath('PYTEST_TMPDIR/test_create_file0')\n"
"\n"
"    def test_create_file(tmp_path):\n"
"        d = tmp_path / \"sub\"\n"
"        d.mkdir()\n"
"        p = d / \"hello.txt\"\n"
"        p.write_text(CONTENT, encoding=\"utf-8\")\n"
"        assert p.read_text(encoding=\"utf-8\") == CONTENT\n"
"        assert len(list(tmp_path.iterdir())) == 1\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_tmp_path.py:11: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_tmp_path.py::test_create_file - assert 0\n"
"============================ 1 failed in 0.12s ============================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:68
msgid "The ``tmp_path_factory`` fixture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:70
msgid ""
"The ``tmp_path_factory`` is a session-scoped fixture which can be used to "
"create arbitrary temporary directories from any other fixture or test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:73
msgid ""
"For example, suppose your test suite needs a large image on disk, which is "
"generated procedurally. Instead of computing the same image for each test "
"that uses it into its own ``tmp_path``, you can generate it once per-session "
"to save time:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:78
msgid ""
"# contents of conftest.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\")\n"
"def image_file(tmp_path_factory):\n"
"    img = compute_expensive_image()\n"
"    fn = tmp_path_factory.mktemp(\"data\") / \"img.png\"\n"
"    img.save(fn)\n"
"    return fn\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"# contents of test_image.py\n"
"def test_histogram(image_file):\n"
"    img = load_image(image_file)\n"
"    # compute and test histogram"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:97
msgid ""
"See :ref:`tmp_path_factory API <tmp_path_factory factory api>` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:103
msgid "The ``tmpdir`` and ``tmpdir_factory`` fixtures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:105
msgid ""
"The ``tmpdir`` and ``tmpdir_factory`` fixtures are similar to ``tmp_path`` "
"and ``tmp_path_factory``, but use/return legacy `py.path.local`_ objects "
"rather than standard :class:`pathlib.Path` objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:110
msgid ""
"These days, it is preferred to use ``tmp_path`` and ``tmp_path_factory``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:112
msgid ""
"In order to help modernize old code bases, one can run pytest with the "
"legacypath plugin disabled:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:115
msgid "pytest -p no:legacypath"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:119
msgid ""
"This will trigger errors on tests using the legacy paths. It can also be "
"permanently set as part of the :confval:`addopts` parameter in the config "
"file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:123
msgid ""
"See :fixture:`tmpdir <tmpdir>` :fixture:`tmpdir_factory <tmpdir_factory>` "
"API for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:130
msgid "The default base temporary directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:132
msgid ""
"Temporary directories are by default created as sub-directories of the "
"system temporary directory.  The base name will be ``pytest-NUM`` where "
"``NUM`` will be incremented with each test run. By default, entries older "
"than 3 temporary directories will be removed. This behavior can be "
"configured with :confval:`tmp_path_retention_count` and :confval:"
"`tmp_path_retention_policy`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:139
msgid ""
"Using the ``--basetemp`` option will remove the directory before every run, "
"effectively meaning the temporary directories of only the most recent run "
"will be kept."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:143
msgid "You can override the default temporary directory setting like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:145
msgid "pytest --basetemp=mydir"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:151
msgid ""
"The contents of ``mydir`` will be completely removed, so make sure to use a "
"directory for that purpose only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/tmp_path.rst:154
msgid ""
"When distributing tests on the local machine using ``pytest-xdist``, care is "
"taken to automatically configure a basetemp directory for the sub processes "
"such that all temporary data lands below a single per-test run basetemp "
"directory."
msgstr ""
